        <p id="An_Intergenerational_Tradition_There’s_a_strong_tradition_of_h">
        <span id="textspan">An Intergenerational Tradition</span><span id="textspan1"><br /></span><span id="textspan2"><br />There’s a strong tradition of hard work in my family. It started back many generations with my grandfather who operated a farm in Milo, Idaho that eventually my Dad bought and worked on. It was a 220 acre farm and as most people know, farmers are known for working hard. You have to work hard in order to meet certain schedules and certain time frames, weather permitting. <br /><br />And so you rose early to milk cows and basically had more jobs than you could possibly get done in a day. It was possible -- depending on how you disciplined your life -- to never stop working. This mentality was instilled in my grandfather as a farmer. My dad grew up on the same farm and continued for 17 years before we moved. </span>
        </p>
        <%= image_tag("KenRay.png", :id => "KenRay", :class => "image") %>
        <p id="And_at_that_point_I_was_8_years_old_so_I_wouldn’t_say_that_I_e">
        At that point I was eight years old, so I wouldn’t say that I experienced the hard work myself. I thought the farm was a wonderful place. For an eight year old it was fun and games. And though I know I did some work, it wasn’t like what my older brothers were doing. Yet, the tradition was there and even though we moved from the farm when I was just a kid in 1965, I was expected to work and work hard. That was the legacy of the farm. <br /><br />After moving off the farm, my dad owned and operated an Article Circle Restaurant and I was expected to help, to clean up, to mow lawns and earn money for my own spending. In those ways I was able to carry on that tradition. I think I was able to carry it on because I’m a hands-on person. I’m a kinesthetic type of worker. I love to fix things, repair things and even if something can’t be easily repaired, I will figure it out. My natural inclination has always been to do it myself.
        </p>
        <%= image_tag("caterpillarred.png", :id => "caterpillarred", :class => "image") %>
        <p id="The_Vision_of_Self-Employment_I_always_felt_--and_it’s_part_of">
        <span id="textspan3">The Vision of Self-Employment</span><span id="textspan4"><br /></span><span id="textspan5"><br />I've always felt --and it’s part of the tradition -- that being a farmer, you really are your own businessman, even though you might not think so. You may not call a farmer an entrepreneur but that’s exactly what he is. The tradition of working hard and being independent came with me from the farm, and my dad exemplified that in my life. My brothers exemplified it as well. I recall them working construction jobs in their teenage years, and a little bit before and after their missions, but we were encouraged by our dad to find a business and make something of ourselves. <br /><br />That's exactly what my brothers did. They started a sprinkling and landscape business right after they came back from their missions. Though I didn’t know what the future held for me or what type of businessman I was going to be, I knew I needed to keep looking and I would find a way to support my family. It was just part of my makeup.<br /></span>
        </p>
        <p id="I_knew_that_I_needed_to_just_keep_looking_and_I_would_be_led_to">
        "I knew that I needed to just keep looking and I would be led to something that would bring about the amount of money I needed to support my whole family, so my wife could stay home and <span id="textspan6">support our children, which was our highest priority."</span>
        </p>
        <p id="For_Cyndi_and_I_our_goals_were_for_her_to_stay_home_with_the_c">
        For Cyndi and I, our goals were for her to stay home with the children. I could not have provided that experience for her or for our children if I were simply a wage earner. You’re just not going to make it with one income in Idaho, so many people find themselves needing to have two incomes to get by. So with those goals in mind, I knew that I needed to just keep looking and I would be led to something that would bring about the amount of money I needed to support my whole family, so my wife could stay home and support our children, which was our highest priority.
        </p>
        <%= image_tag("birdfamindoor.png", :id => "birdfamindoor", :class => "image") %>
        <p id="What_I_learned_from_my_brothers_who_started_their_own_businesse">
        What I learned from my brothers who started their own businesses was the fact that I could do it. I’m fortunate to have a father and a family that was extremely supportive. As I’ve grown up and seen the world from a bigger view, many people don’t have those blessings. It’s a tremendous advantage to have a father who could show you how to work and a mother who could teach you compassion and who was at home to help you on the feminine side of things with social cues and things. It was just very important to have that support. So I knew that when the time came and I needed to make those decisions - Do I want to start this little business here? - Can I do this? I already knew the answer, that I could try. 
        </p>
        <p id="“I_knew_that_when_the_time_came_and_I_needed_to_make_those_deci">
        <span id="textspan7">“I knew that when the time came and I needed to make those decisions -- Do I want to start this little business here? Can I do this? --I already knew the answer, </span><span id="textspan8">that I could try</span><span id="textspan9">.”</span> 
        </p>
        <p id="And_I_may_fail_In_fact_there_were_several_times_when_I_starte">
        And I may fail. In fact, there were several times when I started little businesses. I won’t go into what they were, they were tiny and little, and at the time there seemed a possibility of earning a decent income. But now that I’m older and more mature, I’m actually quite embarrassed to think that I even attempted them and that I would let people talk me into doing some woodworking task which would not pay out in the long run. But I think in my 20’s I was led a little bit more by my enthusiasm. I just wanted to stay busy doing things, working hard and hoping the pay would come later. <br /><br />At the same time, I had to research prospects and see if they would meet my long-term goals. As I got older and hit my 30’s, I was able to see opportunities with better lenses. I could see better, I could see further and I had some experience under my belt by working for others that really made all the difference.
        </p>
        <br><br><br>

        <%= image_tag("apartmentstitle.png", :id => "apartmentstitle", :class => "image") %>
        
        <p id="Our_First_Business_Cyndi_and_I_had_been_married_a_little_over_">
        <span id="textspan10">Our First Business<br /></span><span id="textspan11"><br /></span><span id="textspan12">Cyndi and I had been married a little over a year when my father presented an opportunity to us to purchase two acres of land close to Ricks college in Rexburg, Idaho. This 6-plex was far from campus, and no one wanted to live that far away. It was owned by a Mr. Wayne Josephson, an older man out of Idaho Falls who was looking to get out of this investment. At the time, Cyndi and I were looking to get going in a direction in our life. For the last year, I had gone into real estate down in Utah and had been unsuccessful. I had come back and was either going to work with my brothers, which I did, or look for other opportunities. So there I was, I’d been married a year, I was 23-24 and this opportunity came for someone to purchase this piece of land at a reasonable price. The only question was, “Could we provide the manpower to get it ready?” This was late July, just a month before school began, and the whole place needed major renovations. &nbsp;<br /><br />So we purchased the 6-plex with the idea of filling it full of 32-34 college boys (with about six to each apartment). Complexes come with reputations and this place was called Campus View, because it overlooked campus, but still most people wouldn’t live there. It was relegated to Ricks College football players and the college subsidized their rent. <br /><br />We ended up needing to make a strong commitment to get this place up and running and rented to 32 men in a month. With the help of my parents full-time and Cyndi and I mega-time, day and night, we worked to make the place presentable. After taking a $10,000 loan from my father for cleaning carpets and installing new doors and flooring, we were able to rent it out and then pay back that loan. <br /><br />We didn’t really have a place to stay, so we moved in to one of the studio apartments, which we eventually converted into a one-bedroom. We didn’t have rent to pay, but we had to remodel and create a bedroom so Cyndi and I could have privacy. <br /><br />For several years, we lived there and Cyndi managed the apartments. In the spring, summer and fall, I worked with my brothers in landscaping, making a good wage. But I was frequently out of town for work, and Cyndi was left with the bulk of the work dealing with the students and performing night checks. Cyndi acquired skills that she, at 21, probably didn’t want at the time. But she did learn them -- and learned them well -- like how to stand up for herself and to football players who were swearing and cussing because you demanded that they pay their rent. She’s the better for it. even though she might not agree with that. <br /></span>
        </p>
