        <p id="For_four_years_we_kept_this_place_pretty_much_full_We_didn’t_">
        For four years, we kept this place pretty much full. We didn’t really make any money, but we saved money. Cyndi was very good at saving money. <br /><br />In 1984, we moved into a home about two blocks away. We changed the name of our complex to The Chaparral, hoping to improve the reputation. And we did; we were able to raise the standards for the young men living there and were able to get into a little bit better clientele. We even raised rents a little bit; it was never enough to go out and buy a car or anything of this nature, but we were able to support ourselves. Cyndi was able to stay at home with our children and take care of our highest priorities. <br /><br />For the first twenty years of owning the place, there was a tremendous amount of work that had to be done year in and year out just to keep it functioning. In the middle of that work, we would sometimes look at each other and say, “Is this really worth it? Why don’t we just sell this place? Move on. Do something else.” And I think we even listed it a time or two. People really weren’t interested. It was too far away from campus [laughing]. For that reason, because there was no great demand and because I think we were also just led, by Cyndi’s intuition and our belief that one day if we were disciplined, if we were persistent -- which is something we were really good at being --  it would all pay off. 
        </p>
        <%= image_tag("chapparal.png", :id => "chapparal", :class => "image") %>
        <p id="“We_were_led_by_Cyndi’s_intuition_and_our_belief_that_one_">
        <span id="textspan15">“We were...led, by Cyndi’s intuition and our belief, that one day, if we were disciplined, </span><span id="textspan16">...it would all pay off.</span><span id="textspan17">”</span> 
        </p>
        <p id="In_the_year_2002-03_Ricks_College_made_the_announcement_that_t">
        In the year 2002-03, Ricks College made the <a id="underline" href="http://www.byui.edu/a-new-kind-of-university/the-announcement">announcement</a> that they were transforming into a four-year university, becoming <a id="underline" href="http://www.byui.edu">Brigham Young University-Idaho (BYU-I)</a>.  During the transition period, all of a sudden people wanted to buy our place and of course we knew the value of it. At that time it had probably tripled in value in a matter of just days because of the college’s announcement. So we went about taking that opportunity and finding a partner. Cyndi and I had very little money or cash to do a project that would require millions of dollars, but we had the land and it put us in the driver’s seat. We were able to find a financial partner we could trust whose name was Randall Harward. We’ve been partners ever since. 
        </p>
        <%= image_tag("apartmentside.png", :id => "apartmentside", :class => "image") %>
        <p id="We_built_the_University_Courtyard_Apartments_a_multi-building_">
        We built the <a id="underline" href="http://ucourtyard.com">University Courtyard Apartments</a>; a multi-building complex of 93 apartments that rent to newlywed couples.<br /><br />By listening to the spirit of persistence and following the examples of my parents, we stuck it out. It became easier to persevere as time went on, as we were just plain blessed for making high-priority goals that kept our sights looking up instead of just looking forward or down. It has been a tremendous blessing and it will continue to bless our family for many years to come.
        </p>

        <%= image_tag("familysmaller.png", :id => "familysmaller", :class => "image") %>
        <p id="_The_Move_to_Full_Independence_listening_to_this_on_audio_is_r">
        <span id="textspan18">The Move to Full Independence</span><span id="textspan19"><br /></span><span id="textspan20">listening to this excerpt is recommended (see right)</span><span id="textspan21"><br /><br /></span><span id="textspan22">Moving from Idaho to Washington presented itself in a couple different ways. Number one was that Cyndi and I started feeling the need to get out on our own. I had been working daily for my brothers at Early Bird Landscaping for many, many years. My whole family interacted frequently on a weekly basis and our social lives revolved mostly around them.<br /><br />The apartments supplied enough </span><span id="textspan23">supplementary income so that Cyndi could stay at home. But I often worked out of state, and it came to the point when Cyndi only had so many hands to care for the children and operate the apartments. &nbsp;We felt that I needed to be home on a steady basis and support her. <br /><br />Then there was the matter of making enough money. What did the future hold? I could see that I wasn’t going to become a partner in Early Bird, which meant that I would always be earning a wage. <br /><br />So all these factors led us to keep investigating and looking for other opportunities. A good friend of mine from school, Cody Howard, had started a franchise business of carpet cleaning in a new way. It was a dry-in-one-hour method. Much like Early Bird Sprinkling, which was a new business back in the 70’s that put sprinkler pipes in the ground that could freeze, we thought that one-hour-to-dry carpet cleaning would give us an edge or a niche in that market. We investigated it further, and I actually went and cleaned some carpets for Cody. <br /><br />I liked it; it was a change from what we would now describe as the difficult position of managing young men and getting them to pay their rent. It was pretty much always a negative encounter if they didn't have it. So knowing that to be the type of business that we were in, we asked ourselves, “Did we want to continue doing that all our life?” And we decided we needed to look elsewhere. The opportunity presented itself to get involved in the carpet cleaning business, so we decided to try it out. <br /><br />It was a positive experience, which was quite surprising to me. You are what you experience each day and I was experiencing extremely happy customers who loved the results that I gave on their carpets after cleaning them. They would even feed me and give me tips. They would be so happy because you came in and solved one of their problems, and it was just a good feeling to jump in the truck at the end of the day having made two to three customers extremely happy. <br /><br />Cyndi and I began discussing getting involved in this franchise and we decided we needed to do it. How we were going to do it was not going to be easy. We had some savings which we had put into buying a home and other investments, but they were small. We needed to decide if we were going to cut some of those investments, sell our home and move to Washington state. Cody, in his forethought was selling states as a territory for cheap -- well, I didn’t think it was cheap back then, but looking back now it was a fire sale. (But that’s how businesses get started. You have to start with the premise that you hope it’s going to provide an income and then grow from there.) So we investigated it and the feeling grew between Cyndi and me that we needed to get involved with this. <br /><br />We weren’t really receiving the warmest responses from our family to do what we wanted to do, which was to move away from family, but we were led to do this because it was fulfilling our higher goals. We wanted to make sure Cyndi stayed at home and raised the children and I could provide enough living income so that she could do that and we would live a comfortable life. We could see the future in doing a franchise working for us. As we look back on it now after 25 years of making that decision, it was a tremendous leap of faith. Cyndi was expecting our fifth child, I had spent most of the summer before working for my Dad for about $1000 a month, and we had a little bit of income from the apartments, but not a lot to live on. </span><br />
        </p>
