        <p id="We_wanted_to_open_up_some_carpet_cleaning_businesses_in_the_sta">
        We wanted to open up some carpet cleaning businesses in the state. We ended opening up five areas as sub-contractor areas. so I put ads in the paper and hired five guys. They provided their own vehicle and I provided carpet cleaning equipment. I hired them and we split the profits 50/50. We did that for almost two years. It was marginally successful; it was more of a worry than anything because I was 700 miles away from the transactions of these businesses in five different cities. We decided if we were going to commit to this, we needed to move to Washington. <br /><br />I came to Washington with my brother Marlon and we went to different areas looking for a place to move to start our business. Carpet cleaning had then turned into a <a id="underline" href="http://www.heavensbest.us"> great franchising opportunity, but the person who cleaned the carpet was the person who made the money. We also knew that I needed to be more experienced in cleaning carpet, so I needed to open up an area of my own. The question was where? We did a lot of investigating, but Cyndi had a roommate who led us to <a id="underline" href="http://vimeo.com/88411706">Wenatchee</a>. She thought that it would be a great fit for us based on her description of what we were looking for, and boy, was it!
        </p>
        <%= image_tag("panoramic.png", :id => "panoramic", :class => "image") %>
        <p id="It_was_a_tremendous_blessing_for_us_to_move_to_and_live_in_Wena">
        It was a tremendous blessing for us to move to and live in Wenatchee. Now I say that from hindsight of 25 years, but at that time, here’s how small our goals were: In 1988 when we moved, our plan was for me to move over here for four months - May, June, July and August - 3.5-4 months, and to get the business started. I lived in a studio apartment in kind of a run down part of town. I cleaned carpets out of the back of my 1982 GMC pickup with a camper shell on the back with two business signs on each side. That was my “business vehicle” and what we lacked in funding we were in overabundance with the thought that I could do it. All I needed to do was work hard. <br /><br />Cyndi and I sat down and we made plans on how we would market our business. The day I pulled into Wenatchee, I was ready to clean carpets. I had flyers that I delivered to the Wenatchee World, they went in the newspaper that next day and in two days after I was moved in the phone was ringing and I was cleaning carpets. My goal for that month was to make at least $2000 gross in order for me to stay in Wenatchee. If I couldn't do that amount it wasn't going to work and I was going to turn around and come back home. So I had three months to prove to myself and to Cyndi and the family and to everyone that I could do this. <br /><br />In the midst of this preparation I started listening to positive self-talk tapes. You can imagine the time I had on my hands after I got done working each day without family around. I would sit down and get all pumped up listening to Florence Nightingale, Think and Grow Rich, Covenant Tapes; there’s a number of them and I still have them, which is ridiculous. They’re still down on the shelves and they’re still there because they remind of what I did and how I did it and how it made me believe that I could do it. <br /><br />So for three months I worked my tail off. I had my son Nate, who was eight years old, come over on occasion and he would go to work with me. As I cleaned and did the work in the customer’s home, he had little jobs to do, but those would end and then he would sit at the table and talk to the homeowner. They'd ask about our family and he'd tell them about his brothers and sisters and how the family would soon be moving to Wenatchee if things went well. I don’t know what he said, but whatever it was it worked. Our marketing plan worked well too and the business just took right off. <br /><br />I’m not saying we made a lot of money, but I made enough to pay the rent and to convince Cyndi to follow me. That was really the crucial thing, and being the supportive wife that she is and always has been, she followed me. I think she was crazy at the time. If we would have reversed shoes, I probably would have said, “No.” She was very good at supporting me even though things looked glum from her side. We pulled into Wenatchee with the entire family in a 27 foot U-haul that I drove. Cyndi came with the other children in the GMC pickup that had no air conditioning in the middle of August. She survived and with very few complaints on her part.<br />
        </p>
