        <p id="Providing_for_Ten_I_look_back_at_Cyndi_and_I_in_our_youth_and_">
        <span id="textspana">Providing for Ten<br /></span><span id="textspana1"><br />I look back at Cyndi and I in our youth and I think, “Did we have eight children out of naivete?” We certainly didn’t feel that way. We felt like we were led, that this is what we wanted. I just felt like the support was there and I was able to have just a sense of can-do that led us into doing a lot of good things. A big part of Idaho tradition was larger families, and being surrounded by that certainly influenced us.<br /><br />I remember bringing home our twin babies and as they were sitting on the kitchen table, I was standing there next to them. Then Cyndi said, “Look what you’ve done, Honey. Look what you’ve got now. How are we gonna support these guys?” My response was, “Well, they’re not going to come home to a mansion, but they’re going to leave from one.” I don’t know where that came from in me. We certainly weren’t living in a mansion, we were living in a little three bedroom home with seven kids. It was crowded; even though that had its blessings, it also has its hardships. I don’t know where that came from; it was just deep inside. I felt able to do it. I was physically able, and I think I had my ladder up against the right trees with the church that I belonged to, with the direction my business was going and I knew that I would be able to pick the fruit eventually if I worked hard enough.</span>
        </p>
