        <p id="A_big_part_of_Idaho_tradition_was_larger_families_and_being_su">
        A big part of Idaho tradition was larger families, and being surrounded by that certainly influenced us. Still, I look back at Cyndi and I in our youth and I think, “Did we do this out of naivete?” We certainly didn’t feel that way. We felt like we were led, and that this -- our family of ten -- is what we wanted. I just felt like the support was there and I was able to have just a sense of can-do  that led us into doing a lot of good things.
        </p>
        <%= image_tag("wheelbarrow.png", :id => "wheelbarrow", :class => "image") %>
        <p id="Because_Cyndi_wanted_a_large_family_and_we_both_wanted_to_have_">
        Because Cyndi wanted a large family and we both wanted to have our children with a mother at home, frugality naturally had to be a part of our lifestyle. I dont think I was raised as frugally as Cyndi was, though I am frugal, but with two people having the same ideals -- despite a different past -- it made a big difference. <br /><br />Confidence grows as you have more experience. Confidence is not able to grow if you’re not receiving support from those around you and from others who are mentors in your life. I think being a member of our church was a blessing because we were surrounded by positive people, leaders who told us that yes you can do this, you just need to be persistent and you need to save. Some of the things we did in order to be frugal was Cyndi always had a savings account. We’ve always put away $200 in at least one account. We’ve done that ever since we were married. That was a number that we liked and that we thought we could afford. <br /><br />Frugality is something that I learned from my dad. What you hear financial people saying about saving a little for your self every month is true. It does teach you. It’s like paying tithing. You don’t have as much money, but you’re able to get more out of the money that you do have because you don’t spend unnecessarily. As for the confidence it takes to raise a large family, I don’t know, I think Cyndi has always wanted a large family and I was willing to go along with that. I knew I could provide for a large family. I just knew that I could do that given the time, energy and background I had. I was confident that I could do it. I don’t think it was an outward confidence, it was more an inward confidence from just sticking to the task at hand. <br /><br />And if my ladder is up the right tree, and it’s a good tree and it’s going to give fruit, then it will eventually pay off. We’ve had several investments that have done that. At the time, did we know they were going to do well? No. And we’ve had some that didn’t do well. I think far and above, we had angels looking over us, helping us make the right decisions. Cyndi also has a great intuition on making decisions. She and I were almost always on the same page, pulling in tandem on the same rope and not against each other. We were able to move steadily in one direction and that has paid off through the years.<br /><br /><br />
        </p>
