            <p id="_Industrious_Mornings_by_Nicole_Cheung_daughter_No_one_exempl">
            <span id="textspana4">Industrious Mornings<br /></span><span id="textspana5">Nicole Cheung, daughter<br /></span><span id="textspana6"><br />No one exemplifies “early to bed, early to rise” as well as Dad. He would often put in several hours work before any of us rose in the morning for family scripture study. To instill this great habit in his children, he cheerily went from room to room waking us up at 6am every morning. He had it down to a routine and there was always a warning that he was coming. Just before 6am, the sound of trumpets would come from the living room downstairs. It started quietly and gradually grew louder and louder. That’s right, the Rocky Soundtrack theme song greeted us every morning and told us that Dad was on the way. We’d dash under the covers before he opened the door and flipped the light on (his secret way to get us out of bed). At that point, we could either painfully suffer under the covers, in the light, with blaring Rocky music or get up and go downstairs for family scripture study. Dad knew what he was doing because we usually chose the latter.</span>
            </p>
