        <p id="_I’ve_never_really_been_a_very_materialistic_person_I_remember">
        I’ve never really been a very materialistic person. I remember my brothers always spending a lot of money on cars, particularly my brother Mike; he always had a nice car and it was a fast car. He worked hard and earned the money and took care of himself very well. But I never aspired to have a big, fast car. I never really aspired to want to have something showy. I think I was just more comfortable being out of the spotlight and just marching to my own drum, doing things the way I wanted to do them. I don’t think it was a sacrifice to go without. It was all for a greater cause if we did. We always ate food that was good and nourishing. When we were young with all the little kids, we rarely ate out; most people didn’t eat out back then, but now it’s a very common thing.<br /><br />I think the habit is learned and then it carries over into different aspects of your life, where you realize, “Ya know, I really don’t need that.”
        </p>
        <p id="“You_realize_‘Ya_know_I_really_don’t_need_that_’”_">
        “You realize, ‘Ya know, I really don’t need that.’” 
        </p>
        <p id="My_things_in_life_that_I_liked_to_do_didn’t_cost_a_lot_I_loved">
        My things in life that I liked to do didn’t cost a lot. I loved to play basketball and do sports; it was my release. And that’s very inexpensive. In Rexburg and in Wenatchee, I was able to go play ball 2-3 times a week. I’d get up early at five o’clock and meet up with a bunch of guys down at our church and we’d play ball from 6-7am. I’d be home by the time the kids were waking up and getting ready to go to school. It worked out great and really fulfilled me.
        </p>

