        <p id="text">
        <span id="textspana14">The Pacific Coast Hike</span><br /><span id="textspana15">Nicole Cheung, daughter</span><br /><br />My family loves camping and hiking, but all of us going at once can be quite an ordeal. Just finding ten backpacks, ten sleeping bags and ten people's worth of gear takes weeks of preparation. Not only that, but my dad loves to camp in style. So of course, we bring along things like steak and other gourmet essentials.<br /><br />The Pacific Coast hike is exotic and breathtaking and feels as though you've stumbled into another world. The Olympic National Rainforest looms to the east as you hike your way down the coast, and it’s necessary to time your hike so the tide drops at just the right moments to get through tricky coastal areas. When it's impossible to get through on the beach, you actually hike up ladders into the rainforest.<br /><br />My dad is always such a trooper on these trips. He is responsible for everyone's comfort and well-being, but also making sure we pull our weight and don't slow things down. It's a fine balance to achieve with eight children of all varying levels of hiking ability. Nothing too crazy happened on this trip (besides a few rainy nights on the beach), but by the end of day five we were all exhausted. We had the option of spending the last night camping on the beach or heading back to civilization. Dad made the executive decision and took us all to a hotel with the best hot tub and pool he could find.<br /><br />Accommodations for ten people at a nice hotel are not cheap and I know my dad didn't have to do it. But he did anyway. I'll never forget showering after that trip and then jumping into the pool and hot tub. We probably all stayed way longer than recommended in the hot tub, but it just felt so good on our hike-worn bodies. It was the perfect way to end an epically amazing camping trip and we owed it all to a generous and doting Dad.<br />
        </p>
